ards''': 1,613 [[Alfred Morris (American football)|Alfred Morris]] (2012)<ref name=singleseason />\n* '''Receptions''': 113 [[Pierre Gar\u00e7on]] (2013)\n* '''Receiving yards''': 1,483 [[Santana Moss]] (2005)<ref name=singlerecords>{{cite news|title=Moss, Portis Set New Franchise Marks|url=https://www.redskins.com/news/moss-portis-set-new-franchise-marks-3456351|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Redskins.com|date=January 2, 2006|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* '''Pass interceptions''': 13 [[Dan Sandifer]] (1948)<ref name=singleseason />\n* '''Sacks''': 18.5 [[Dexter Manley]] (1986)\n* '''Forced fumbles''': 6 [[LaVar Arrington]] (2003)\n* '''Field goals made''': 33 [[Mark Moseley]] (1983)<ref name=singleseason />\n* '''Points''': 161 [[Mark Moseley]] (1983)<ref name=singleseason />\n* '''Total touchdowns''': 24 [[John Riggins]] (1983)<ref name=singleseason />\n* '''Punt return average''' (minimum 5 returns): 24.3 [[Derrick Shepard (wide receiver)|Derrick Shepard]] (1987)<ref name=\"pro-football-reference.com\">{{cite web| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/was/single-season-returns.htm| title=Washington Redskins Kick & Punt Returns Single-Season Register| accessdate=December 28, 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206152906/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/was/single-season-returns.htm| archive-date=December 6, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''Kickoff return average''' (minimum 5 returns): 42.8 Hail Haynes (1950)<ref name=\"pro-football-reference.com\"/>\n* '''Punting average''': 51.4* [[Sammy Baugh]] (1940)<ref>{{cite web | work=Professional Football Hall of Fame | url=http://www.profootballhof.com/history/release.jsp?release_id=2557 | title=Oldest Individual Single-Season and Single-Game Records | accessdate=December 29, 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106194629/http://www.profootballhof.com/history/release.jsp?release_id=2557 | archive-date=January 6, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n''* Also an NFL record''\n\n==Redskins career records==\n* '''Passing yards''': 25,206 [[Joe Theismann]] (1974\u20131985)<ref name=firstgames>{{cite web | work=[[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] | url=http://www.profootballhof.com/history/team.jsp?franchise_id=32 | title=Washington Redskins: Firsts, Records, Odds & Ends | accessdate=April 5, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528072731/http://www.profootballhof.com/history/team.jsp?franchise_id=32 | archive-date=May 28, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* '''Passing touchdowns''': 187 [[Sammy Baugh]] (1937\u20131952)\n* '''Rushing yards''': 7,472 [[John Riggins]] (1976\u20131979,1981\u20131985)<ref name=firstgames />\n* '''Receptions''': 889 [[Art Monk]] (1980\u20131993)<ref name=firstgames />\n* '''Receiving yards''': 12,029 [[Art Monk]] (1980\u20131993)<ref name=records>{{cite web|title=Career Stats Leaders|url=https://www.redskins.com/team/history/career-stats-leaders|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Redskins.com|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* '''Pass interceptions''': 54 [[Darrell Green]] (1983\u20132002)<ref name=records />\n* '''Field goals made''': 263 [[Mark Moseley]] (1974\u20131986)\n* '''Points''': 1,207 [[Mark Moseley]] (1974\u20131986)<ref name=firstgames />\n* '''Total touchdowns''': 90 [[Charley Taylor]] (1964\u20131977)\n* '''Punt return average''' (minimum 25 returns): 13.8.0 [[Bob Seymour]] (1941\u20131944)<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/was/career-returns.htm | title=Washington Redskins Kick & Punt Returns Career Register | accessdate=December 28, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206150046/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/was/career-returns.htm | archive-date=December 6, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* '''Kickoff return average''' (minimum 25 returns): 28.5 [[Bobby Mitchell]] (1962\u20131968)<ref name=\"http\"/>\n* '''Punting average''': 45.1 [[Sammy Baugh]] (1937\u20131952)\n* '''Sacks''': 91 [[Dexter Manley]] (1981\u20131989)<ref name=records />\n* '''Forced fumbles''': 17 [[Charles Mann (American football)|Charles Mann]] (1983\u20131993)\n\n==Single-game records==\n* '''Receptions''': 14 [[Roy Helu]] (2011)<ref name=singlegame>{{cite news|last=Kring-Schreifels|first=Jake|title=Rewarding Moments In Redskins History: Helu & Gano Make History|url=https://www.redskins.com/news/rewarding-moments-in-redskins-history-helu-gano-make-history-16226482|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Redskins.com|date=November 2, 2017|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* '''Completions''': 33 [[Jason Campbell]] (2007), [[Kirk Cousins]] (2015)\n* '''Longest field goal''': 59 yards [[Graham Gano]] (2011)<ref name=\"singlegame\"/>\n* '''Sacks''': 4 [[Dexter Manley]] (1988), [[Ken Harvey (American football)|Ken Harvey]] (1997), [[Phillip Daniels]] (2005), [[Brian Orakpo]] (2009), [[Ryan Kerrigan]] (2014)\n* '''Interceptions''': 4 [[Deangelo Hall]]\n\n==NFL records==\n===Offense===\n* The Washington Redskins have had two 14-win seasons, in [[1983 Washington Redskins season|1983]] and [[1991 Washington Redskins season|1991]].<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/gameswon | title=Team Records: Games Won | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106104033/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/gameswon | archive-date=January 6, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins scored 541 points in 1983, which is the sixth highest total in a season of all time.<ref name=recordscoring>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/scoring | title=Team Records: Scoring | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091201115816/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/scoring | archive-date=December 1, 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins' 72 points against the [[New York Giants]] on November 27, 1966, are the most points ever scored by an NFL team in a regular season game, and the 72 to 41 score amounted to 113 points and the highest-scoring game ever in NFL history.<ref name=recordscoring /> The second-half scoring for the game amounted to 65 points, the second-highest point total for second-half scoring and the third-highest total scoring in any half in NFL history.<ref name=recordscoring /> The Redskins' 10 touchdowns are the most by a team in a single game, and the 16 total touchdowns are the most combined for a game.<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/touchdowns | title=Team Records: Touchdowns | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228052804/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/touchdowns | archive-date=December 28, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref> The Redskins' nine [[extra point|PATs]] are the second most all-time for a single game, and the 14 combined PATs are the most ever in a game.<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/pat | title=Team Records: Points After Touchdown | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102050027/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/pat | archive-date=January 2, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins set a record for most first downs in a game with 39 in a game against the Lions on November 4, 1990. They also set a record by not allowing a single first down against the Giants on September 27, 1942.<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/firstdowns | title=Team Records: First Downs | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102035159/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/firstdowns | archive-date=January 2, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins have led the league in passing eight times: in 1938, 1940, 1944, 1947\u201348, 1967, 1974 and 1989. Only the [[San Diego Chargers]] have led more times.<ref name=passing>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/passing | title=Team Records: Passing | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227171500/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/passing | archive-date=December 27, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref> The Redskins led the league in completion percentage 11 times: in 1937, 1939\u20131940, 1942\u201345, 1947\u201348 and 1969\u20131970, second only to the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref name=passing /> Their four straight years from 1942\u201345 is the second longest streak.\n* The Redskins' nine sacks allowed in 1991 are the third fewest allowed in a season.<ref name=passing />\n* The Redskins completed 43 passes in an overtime win against [[Detroit Lions|Detroit]] on November 4, 1990, second most all-time.<ref name=passing />\n\n===Defense===\n* The Redskins recovered eight opponent's fumbles against the [[St. Louis Cardinals (NFL)|St. Louis Cardinals]] on October 25, 1976, the most ever in one game.<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/fumbles | title=Team Records: Fumbles | accessdate=January 12, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113044845/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/fumbles | archive-date=January 13, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins allowed 82 first downs in [[1937 Washington Redskins season|1937]], third fewest all-time.<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/firstdowns | title=Defense Records: First Downs | accessdate=January 12, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113225051/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/firstdowns | archive-date=January 13, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins have led the league in fewest total yards allowed five times, 1935\u201337, 1939, and 1946, which is the third most.<ref name=fewestyards>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/netyards | title=Defense Records: Net Yards Allowed | accessdate=January 12, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117235537/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/netyards | archive-date=January 17, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> Their three consecutive years from 1935\u201337 is an NFL record.<ref name=fewestyards />\n* The Redskins have led the league in fewest passing yards allowed seven times, in 1939, 1942, 1945, 1952\u201353, 1980, and 1985, second only to Green Bay (10).<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/passing | title=Defense Records: Passing | accessdate=January 12, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112155007/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/passing | archive-date=January 12, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins had 61 defensive turnovers in [[1983 Washington Redskins season|1983]], the third most all-time.<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/turnovers | title=Defense Records: Turnovers | accessdate=January 12, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080127140638/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/turnovers | archive-date=January 27, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> The turnover differential of +43 that year was the highest of all time.\n* The Redskins had only 12 defensive turnovers in [[2006 Washington Redskins season|2006]], the fewest in a 16-game season and second all time. (The [[Baltimore Colts]] had 11 turnovers in the strike-shortened [[1982 NFL Season|1982 Season]] which lasted only 9 games.)<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/turnovers | title=Defense Records: Turnovers | accessdate=July 16, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504035342/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/def/turnovers | archive-date=May 4, 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Special teams===\n* The Redskins led the league in field goals for eight seasons, {{nfly|1945}}, {{nfly|1956}}, {{nfly|1971}}, {{nfly|1976}}\u2013[[1977 NFL season|77]], {{nfly|1979}}, {{nfly|1982}}, {{nfly|1992}}. Only the [[Green Bay Packers]] have ever led more.<ref name=fieldgoals>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/fieldgoals | title=Team Records: Field goals | accessdate=January 2, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224090641/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/fieldgoals | archive-date=December 24, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins and Bears attempted an NFL record 11 field goals on November 14, 1971, and the Redskins and Giants tied that mark on November 14, 1976.<ref name=fieldgoals />\n* The Redskins 28 consecutive games, from {{nfly|1988}} to {{nfly|1990}}, scoring a field goal is third all time.<ref name=fieldgoals />\n* The Redskins have led the league in punting average six times, in 1940\u201343, 1945, and 1958, second only to the [[Denver Broncos]].<ref name=punting>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/punting | title=Team Records: Punting | accessdate=January 12, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227144123/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/punting | archive-date=December 27, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref> Their four consecutive years from 1940\u201343 is an NFL record.<ref name=punting />\n* The Redskins have led the league in average kickoff return yards eight times, in 1942, 1947, 1962\u201363, 1973\u201374, 1981, and 1995, more than any other team.<ref>{{cite web | work=National Football League | url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/kickreturns | title=Team Records: Kickoff returns | accessdate=January 12, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226171715/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/team/kickreturns | archive-date=December 26, 2007 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Redskins all time FG record is 59yds (4 shy of tying the all-time NFL Record). It was set 11\u201306\u201311 by Graham Gano against the San Francisco 49ers at FedexField.\n\n==Broadcasting==\n{{Main|List of Washington Redskins broadcasters}}\n\n===Radio===\nThe Redskins' [[flagship station]] is [[WTEM]], ''The Team 980''; it had been acquired by [[Red Zebra Broadcasting]], a group co-owned with the Redskins by Snyder.<ref>{{cite news | work=Washington Post | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/16/AR2008071602425.html | title=Snyder's Simulcast Plans Center on WTEM | accessdate=July 17, 2008 | first=Paul | last=Farhi | date=July 17, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626131811/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/16/AR2008071602425.html | archive-date=June 26, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, the station was sold to [[Urban One]], but maintained its rights to the team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/168506/urban-one-acquires-980-wtem-washington-from-redskins/|title=Urban One Acquires 980 WTEM Washington From Redskins|date=2018-05-23|work=RadioInsight|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813072318/https://radioinsight.com/headlines/168506/urban-one-acquires-980-wtem-washington-from-redskins/|archive-date=August 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Paras|first1=Matthew|title=Dan Snyder sells The Team 980 to Urban One|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/may/21/dan-snyder-sells-team-980-urban-one/|website=Washington Times|accessdate=21 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726175319/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/may/21/dan-snyder-sells-team-980-urban-one/|archive-date=July 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2019, it was announced that [[Cumulus Media]] had acquired the team's radio rights as well, and would move it to [[WSBN|WMAL]]. Concurrently, WMAL was to be re-launched as an [[ESPN Radio]] affiliate, WSBN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/local-networks/espn-cumulus-dc-sports-radio-redskins.html|title=ESPN and Cumulus will launch a new D.C. ESPN Radio station|date=2019-06-14|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615115453/https://awfulannouncing.com/local-networks/espn-cumulus-dc-sports-radio-redskins.html|archive-date=June 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/187183/wmal-a-f-washington-d-c-to-split-simulcast-am-to-f|title=WMAL-A-F/Washington, D.C. To Split Simulcast, AM To Flip To Sports As ESPN 630, The Sports Capitol|website=All Access|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702014601/https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/187183/wmal-a-f-washington-d-c-to-split-simulcast-am-to-f|archive-date=July 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[WMAL-FM]] still carries broadcasts of Redskins games.\n\nAs of the 2019 season, Larry Michael is the voice of the Redskins on the radio. He took this role in 2004 after longtime announcer [[Frank Herzog]] left.<ref>{{cite web|work=GW Hatchet |url=http://media.www.gwhatchet.com/media/storage/paper332/news/2005/01/31/Sports/Larry.Michael.D.c.s.Most.Versatile.Voice-846364.shtml |title=Larry Michael: D.C.'s most versatile voice |accessdate=December 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529234914/http://media.www.gwhatchet.com/media/storage/paper332/news/2005/01/31/Sports/Larry.Michael.D.c.s.Most.Versatile.Voice-846364.shtml |archivedate=May 29, 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref name=announcers>{{cite news | work=Washington Times | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb5244/is_200402/ai_n19592633 | title=WJFK replaces Herzog; L. Michael joins Jurgensen, Huff | accessdate=December 27, 2007}}{{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref name=announcers />\n\nMichael is joined by analysts [[Chris Cooley (American football)|Chris Cooley]] and, until the end of the 2018 season, Hall of Famer [[Sonny Jurgensen]]. Jurgensen is a former Redskins quarterback who had been in broadcasting since he retired from the team in 1974, much of that time spent working for his former team. Cooley played tight end for the Redskins from 2004 until 2012 and made the Pro Bowl twice. Cooley replaced Hall of Famer [[Sam Huff]], a former linebacker who played several years with the Redskins, as color commentator following Huff's retirement at the end of the 2012 season.\n\nAnother former Washington tight end, [[Rick \"Doc\" Walker]], is the [[sideline reporter]] and Kevin Sheehan hosts the team's pregame show, while Scott Jackson hosts the halftime and postgame shows. Longtime Redskins running back/receiver/return man [[Brian Mitchell (American football)|Brian Mitchell]], as well as former running back [[Clinton Portis]] and defensive back [[Fred Smoot]], also contribute to broadcasts.\n\n===Radio affiliates===\n[[File:Washington Redskins radio affiliates.png|thumb|right|Map of radio affiliates]]\nWashington Redskins radio affiliates include:<ref>{{cite web|title=Radio Network|url=https://www.redskins.com/news/radio-network|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Redskins.com|date=August 15, 2018|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====District of Columbia====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins|border=2}};\"|City !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins|border=2}};\"|Call Sign !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins|border=2}};\"|Frequency\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]|| [[WTEM]] / W240DJ